  displayName: Pear Tree
  audioClip: {fileID: 8300000, guid: 6928089ad90781a49a8a9a026a48fbed, type: 3}
  environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
  environmentLayers: []
  environmentVerticalOffset: 0
  poem:
    text: 'Birnenschmaus


      So come, dear sunshine,

      Make our pears grow
      well!

      And when they have turned golden,

      Then come and blow, dear
      wind!

      Come, wind, and rustle every branch

      And invite us all to
      be your guests!

      We will hurry out of the house

      And hold a pear
      feast.


      August Heinrich Hoffmann von Fallersleben'
    contextImage: {fileID: 0}
    imageWidth: 0.5
    imageFeather: -1
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
    environmentLayers: []
    environmentVerticalOffset: 0
  contextInfos:
  - text: "Pear, French Cuisine\nLouis XIV named the pear a royal fruit, and his
      obsession was sincere. It was his greatest fruit love after figs \u2014 his
      gardener La Quintinie raised fifty varieties for the royal table, and Louis
      sent his favourite, the Bon Chr\xE9tien, as gifts to other heads of state.
      It entered French haute cuisine and has never left."
    contextImage: {fileID: 0}
    imageWidth: 0.5
    imageFeather: -1
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
    environmentLayers: []
    environmentVerticalOffset: 0
  - text: "Les Adeuineax amoreux\nTrois moines passoient\nTrois poires pendoient\nChascum
      en prist une\nEt s\u2019en demouras deux.\nL\u2019Explication: L\u2019un des
      moines avoit nom Chascun.\n\nThree monks were passing\nThree pears were hanging\nEach
      took one\nAnd two remained.\n\nExplanation: One of the monks was named Each"
    contextImage: {fileID: 0}
    imageWidth: 0.5
    imageFeather: -1
    environmentPainting: {fileID: 0}
    environmentLayers: []
    environmentVerticalOffset: 0
